ng young sociologist William Edward Burghardt Du Bois (1868–1963) was given a temporary post as Assistant in Sociology at the University of Pennsylvania in order to conduct a systematic investigation of social conditions in the seventh ward of Philadelphia. The product of those studies was the first great empirical book on the Negro in American society.More than one hundred years after its original publication by the University of Pennsylvania Press, The Philadelphia Negro remains a classic work. It is the first, and perhaps still the finest, example of engaged sociological scholarship—the kind of work that, in contemplating social reality, helps to change it.In his introduction, Elijah Anderson examines how the neighborhood studied by Du Bois has changed over the years and compares the status of blacks today with their status when the book was initially published.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxSocial conditions. 0aHousehold employeeszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAfrican-American Studies.  aAlcohol.  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aBetterment.  aBlack.  aBooks of Regional Interest.  aChurch religion.  aCivics.  aCrime.  aDemographics.  aEducation.  aEmancipation.  aEmployment.  aFamily.  aGreat migration.  aHealth.  aHousing.  aIntermarriage.  aJobs.  aMarriage.  aNegro.  aOccupation.  aPhiladelphia.  aPolitics.  aPoverty.  aProfessions.  aRace.  aRecreation.  aSeventeenth eighteenth nineteenth century.  aSeventh Ward.  aSocial Science.  aSociology.  aSuffrage.  aW. E. B. Du Bois first work.  aWharton School.  afreedmen.  ainterviews.  amapping.  amodel.  amoment in time.  astatistics.1 aAnderson, Elijah, 